name: FFH Hotel T-Shirt
description:
In the late 1800s, single-room occupancy hotels began popping up around major cities across the United States.  Housing many of the transient workers that were responsible for constructing the buildings throughout New York, and Chicago, these hotels were also called home to some of the poorest people living amongst the urban development.  

The most common facility at the turn of the century was the "Cage Hotel."  These were lofts or other large, open buildings that were subdivided into tiny cubicles using boards or sheets of corrugated iron. Since these walls were always one to three feet short of the floor or ceiling, the open space was sealed off with chicken wire, hence the name “cage hotels.” Heat, lighting, ventilation, and sanitary conditions were abysmal and owners could pack as many as 200 men on a floor.

This shirt was inspired by the only unique aspect SRO's had to offer...The interesting signage that hung outside the establishment.

For maximum longevity, wash inside out in cold water, and line dry or dry inside-out on low.

Black ink printed onto 50/50 Royal Blue American Apparel Tees.

name: Veins of New York City T-Shirt
description:
New York City's transit system is one of the world's most sophisticated means of transportation.  The first underground transit demonstration took place in 1869, but was never developed further due to financial, and political reasons.  One year earlier, the first elevated train was erected.  By 1904, the first underground line was fully completed, and New York City was on its way to becoming what it is today.

Anyone who loves New York City can respect this shirt.  Even if they've been late to work, or missed a meeting.  

Where else can you see a full band perform for free underneath an amazing city at 1am on a Wednesday?  The MTA, for better or worse has become the arterial pathway of this major city.

For maximum longevity, wash inside out in cold water, and line dry or dry inside-out on low.

name: Veins of Chicago T-Shirt
description:
The oldest sections of the 'EL' started operating in 1892, making it the second-oldest rapid transit system in the Americas, after New York City.  One of the cheapest, self-navigated tours in the city is riding around the loop, and soaking in all of Chicago's wonderful architecture.

In 1947, the Chicago Rapid Transit Company and the Chicago Surface Lines streetcar system. In 1952, CTA purchased the assets of the Chicago Motor Coach Company, which was under the control of Yellow Cab founder John D. Hertz, resulting in a fully unified system.

Like the Veins of New York City t-shirt, Veins of Chicago represents the love for a city through its transit system.  Even if you hate it, it's still a beautiful site to behold one night on a downtown adventure.

For maximum longevity, wash inside out in cold water, and line dry or dry inside-out on low.

name: King Louis IX T-Shirt
description:

name: Agora (The Meeting Place) T-Shirt
description:
Created by Magdalena Abakanowicz, this permanent installation located in downtown Chicago is comprised of 106 nine-foot tall headless torsos made of cast iron.  The artwork derives its name from the Greek word for "meeting place."  

Being deeply affected by World War II and the forty-five years of Soviet domination that followed, Abakanowicz began sculpting headless torsos in the 1970s as a representation of the mindless marches, and parades that ultimately celebrated mass murderers.

Originally titled "Walk This Way," this t-shirt was designed as a reminder to not follow the path of others in front of you just because it is the simplest solution at the time.

For maximum longevity, wash inside out in cold water, and line dry or dry inside-out on low.

name: Building Blocks of Chicago T-Shirt
description:
Frank Lloyd Wright developed a basic understanding of geometric shapes by using Froebul Blocks as a child.  As an adult, Wright created some of the most innovative pieces of architecture in Chicago, and around the world.  He credited his mother, and the educational toy with his understanding of shapes in relation to architecture.

In 1916, John L. Wright, son of Frank, created Lincoln logs.  A children's toy consisting of notched miniature logs, used to build miniature forts and buildings. 

This t-shirt pays homage to Chicago, Frank Lloyd Wright, and gettin' ya learn on...one block at a time.

For maximum longevity, wash inside out in cold water, and line dry or dry inside-out on low.
